Happy to take a look into this one, seems to be a few issues around the trace calls which could be related perhaps.  I'd imagine we'd get the same issue showing on Goerli chain here?

I'll take a look at spinning up a node using OE and can go from there.

Sorry to interject, but I would be interested to learn how you can "spin up" an OE node. I'm just curious. First, it's been my experience in the past that syncing OE takes literally months. Do you have an existing database? Also, I'm curious -- would it even sync as OE didn't transition to post-merge.

I don't intend this comment to be critical in any way, so please excuse me if it sounds that way. I'm just genuinely curious because I might want to some day do the same.

Hi @tjayrush, it's a first time for me to start an OE node so just going over their docs, no prior knowledge or DB at my end :).

My plan for this issue would be to start syncing goerli to keep the size small and hopefully sync in a day or so rather than weeks++ (if that's possible).  I wasn't aware about OE not transitioning post merge.... does that render this a little redundant now @AlexeyAkhunov?  Or we can press on and focus on pre-merge blocks looking at the differences there?

I've used Nethermind (which did transition to post-merge) to compare Mainnet trace results in the past. I can't speak for them, of course, but you might be able to get access to their semi-public endpoints. I can connect you if you need.

I'll close this one, as we're not getting any issues raised from fuzzing against go ethereum (which I'd expect to highlight this particular inconsistency), and afaics the open eth project is now archived on github.
